I don't think that we need to do this recursively.

The list of resources is a topological sort of the reverse-dependency graph, so any resource R will appear in the list before its dependents and its children. This implies that given R, we can find all of its direct dependents and children via a linear scan of the list starting from R. By induction, we can find all of the transitive dependents and children of R via the same linear scan. So this can just be the following:

